<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-416-146  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 416 146.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  July 10 1989 v6 n27 p8(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Word for Windows has BASIC appeal.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Smith, Gina.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Microsoft Corp's new Microsoft Word for Windows package containsan embedded programming language similar to BASIC.andP;  The firmintends to release a series of applications, both for Windows andfor the OS-2 Presentation Manager, which share this embeddedlanguage as well as a powerful macro language and recorder.andO;Excel, Microsoft Project and other database and presentationgraphics packages are expected to use the new languages.andP;  Theenhancements are intended to allow users to customize theirprograms and to share routines between Windows and PresentationManager products.andP;  Eventually, Microsoft will extend thesecapabilities across entire networks.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (products).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   Microsoft Word for Windows (Word processing software) (design andconstruction).andO;Topic:     Software packagesWord ProcessingProgramming LanguagesMacrosApplicationsSoftware Design.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Word for Windows' BASIC-like programming language is a key element inMicrosoft Corp.'s strategy to create an integrated suite of Windows and OS/2Presentation Manager applications.andM;Before the end of next year, sources report, Microsoft plans to release aseries of Windows and Presentation Manager (PM) applications that share thesame embedded language, as well as a powerful macro language and recorder.andO;These applications will include versions of Excel and Microsoft Project, aswell as future database and presentation-graphics offerings.andM;With consistent programming and macro languages, users will be able todevelop customized menus and programs, and combine BASIC-like programmingcommands with prerecorded macro commands to create complex routines that spanthese applications, sources said.andM;&quot;The advantage [of an embedded BASIC] is that users will be able to do a lotof sexy things they could never do before, do it all in Windows or PM, and doit with a lot less training,&quot; said one micro manager who asked not to beidentified.andM;In a prerelease copy of Word for Windows, the embedded language -- calledWord BASIC -- contains more than 100 BASIC-like commands.andM;Because PM and Windows applications will share these common languages, a usercould define and record a routine to check sales figures recorded in an Excelspreadsheet, extract them and insert the numbers into a specified memo filestored in Word for Windows.andP;  The addition of BASIC-like programmingcapabilities will allow users to add more sophisticated programmingtechniques, such as &quot;if .andP;  .  .  then&quot; logic, into their routines.andM;The macro that checks sales figures in Excel, for example, could updatedifferent memos based on the values in the spreadsheet.andP;  If sales were up,congratulatory memos could be updated; a disciplinary memo could be issuedfor disappointing figures.andM;Eventually, Microsoft plans to provide the same capability to separate PCslinked on a network, with a network version of the dynamic data exchange(DDE) protocol in Windows and PM, sources said.andM;-- Gina Smith</TEXT></DOC>